    "data_flow": "1) Client submits PlaceOrder request → Saga Orchestrator creates a new saga instance (state: STARTED, step: 1). 2) Orchestrator sends CreateOrder to Order Service → on success, persists state (step: 2, completedSteps: [ORDER_CREATED]). 3) Sends ReserveItems to Inventory Service → on success, persists state (step: 3, completedSteps: [ORDER_CREATED, ITEMS_RESERVED]). 4) Sends ChargeCustomer to Payment Service → on success, persists state (step: 4, completedSteps: [..., PAYMENT_CHARGED]). 5) Sends AssignCourier to Courier Service → on success, saga completes (status: COMPLETED). On ANY step failure: orchestrator walks completedSteps in reverse, invoking each compensation command. After all compensations succeed, saga status → COMPENSATED. If a compensation itself fails, saga status → COMPENSATION_FAILED and an alert fires for manual intervention.",
    "patterns_used": [
      { "pattern": "Orchestration Saga", "rationale": "The flow is strictly sequential with a linear dependency chain. Orchestration makes the step order and compensation logic explicit in one place, which is critical for debugging payment/inventory failures. Choreography would scatter this logic across 4 services, making it harder to reason about partial failure states." },
