      "decision": "Async message broker commands over synchronous HTTP",
      "gains": "Decouples orchestrator from service availability. Built-in retry and dead-letter semantics. Survives transient service outages without saga failure.",
      "sacrifices": "Adds infrastructure complexity (broker). Slightly higher latency per step. Requires idempotency handling at every consumer.",
      "alternatives_considered": ["Synchronous HTTP with retries: simpler infrastructure but tight temporal coupling — if a service is down, the saga blocks or fails immediately."]
    },
    {
      "decision": "Persist saga state before each step",
      "gains": "Crash recovery: if the orchestrator dies mid-saga, a new instance can resume from the last persisted state. No lost or orphaned sagas.",
      "sacrifices": "One additional DB write per step adds latency (~1-5ms each). Total overhead for a 4-step saga: 4-20ms.",
      "alternatives_considered": ["In-memory state only: faster but unrecoverable on crash. Unacceptable for financial transactions."]
